“The upcoming UK local elections are increasingly being viewed by markets as a broader referendum on political stability and fiscal credibility. Polling points toward a highly fragmented political landscape with rising support for Reform UK and weakening support for traditional parties. While these are local elections, markets are closely monitoring the implications for future fiscal policy, leadership stability, and gilt market dynamics, especially in an environment already challenged by sticky inflation and geopolitical energy shocks.”  

Markets are increasingly focused on the political stability of the Starmer government ahead of next week’s UK local elections. Polling and media reporting suggest Labour could face significant local-election losses, which has increased internal leadership speculation around figures such as Angela Rayner and Andy Burnham. From a market perspective, the key issue is not immediate government change, but whether rising political fragmentation begins to impact fiscal credibility, gilt market stability, and sterling sentiment at a time when the UK is already dealing with sticky inflation and weaker growth dynamics.”